I am just getting started and trying to help my daughter with getting vision setup on a raspberryPi. I have installed the latest beta items from PhotoVision and WPILIB.

  • photonvision-dev-v2024.1.1-beta-3.2-25-g0356eeeb-linuxarm64-image_RaspberryPi.xz
  • Release WPILib 2024.1.1 Beta 4 Release · wpilibsuite/allwpilib · GitHub

I can get PhotoVision up and running. I can see it via the browser of my PC. I calibrated the camera and it can identify April Tags. I can see the target information in that webpage view.

However, when I try to run the code using PhotonLib as they direct, I am getting an error message. It would seem that the WPILIB code is expecting the camera to be under an extra path in the network tables (/photonvision/Logitech_BRIO). However, it does* see the camera under the network tables (just* Logitech_BRIO) but it seems it won’t connect to that one without the extra path in the name. Is the code out of date for this mixture of beta versions? Do they need to update it so it looks for the cameras in the right spot? Or have I missed some other config somewhere?

Thanks!

Ultimately, the information in this post is what solved this item for me.

Essentially, PhotonVision is typically setup with just a Team Number. When you do that however, it is automatically trying to look for NetworkTables at a very specific location which is how the RoboRIO would standardly be setup. However, this is not how a PC running on the same network will be setup. So, PhotonVision will not see the networktables running on your PC if you enter a team number.

With the latest version of PhotonVision, however, you can setup an IP address or hostname of where the network tables are running. So, you should enter the information of the PC where you are Simulating your robot (and it boots up network tables). Then PhotonVision will connect to these network tables and post the information. Then you can use the regular PhotonLib code in your VisualStudio code to connect to the camera via the network tables and get the target information etc.
